-Right. You come in your house…
-Right, right. And it's there.

00:11:40.817 --> 00:11:43.836
-I'm there. Yeah.
-I'm there. Yeah.

00:11:44.073 --> 00:11:46.145
But B Smooth was doing so good, man.

00:11:46.145 --> 00:11:47.715
He was, you know…

00:11:47.715 --> 00:11:49.177
Everybody been doing good.

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:51.663
We're doing good now.

00:11:51.663 --> 00:11:52.540
Yeah.

00:11:52.983 --> 00:11:55.983
-You guys, you guys worry about
these places being bought up?

00:11:56.500 --> 00:11:58.579
Like the spillover from downtown?

00:11:58.579 --> 00:11:59.965
That's what JoJo is telling me.

00:11:59.965 --> 00:12:01.367
Our neighborhood gone now.

00:12:01.955 --> 00:12:03.835
SCAD done bought everything.

00:12:03.835 --> 00:12:05.183
They started with one school.

00:12:05.183 --> 00:12:07.368
See,
you'll keep hearing that all day long.

00:12:07.368 --> 00:12:09.666
SCAD started with one school
on Henry Street.

00:12:09.666 --> 00:12:10.810
Mm-hmm.

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:12.560
SCAD ain't through with us yet.

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:15.187
-What would you want to say to them?

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:16.410
Um,

00:12:16.603 --> 00:12:18.739
SCAD, make some affordable houses

00:12:19.007 --> 00:12:21.622
for the African-Americans in Savannah.

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:23.510
We was here before y'all.

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:28.387
Now we got our rent up
to $1,500, $1,200.

00:12:28.387 --> 00:12:30.560
-Your rent's $1,500?
-$1,500.

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:31.560
How many bedrooms?

00:12:32.186 --> 00:12:34.140
-One.
-Seriously?

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.090
Like a one bedroom here is $1,500?

00:12:36.090 --> 00:12:38.410
Um, this a three and this is a two.

00:12:38.678 --> 00:12:41.480
These are like $1,700, $1,900.

00:12:41.480 --> 00:12:42.840
-Really?
-Right.

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:47.060
We grew up in these houses
for $375 a month.

00:12:47.060 --> 00:12:48.506
-Exactly. Hallelujah.

00:12:48.506 --> 00:12:50.022
$275 a month.

00:12:51.528 --> 00:12:54.136
We get paid seven dollars and fifty cent

00:12:54.556 --> 00:12:56.016
an hour for labor.

00:12:56.016 --> 00:12:57.016
-Where do you work?

00:12:58.850 --> 00:13:01.516
I don't work,
but the minimum wage is…

00:13:01.516 --> 00:13:03.395
-$7.50?
-It's $7.50.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:06.490
I'm too old to work.
Now I'm 66, right?

00:13:06.496 --> 00:13:08.721
-Oh, you're a spring chicken, come on.
-[laughs]

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:12.094
Hey, Jojo and I shop at the same place.

00:13:12.094 --> 00:13:13.345
-That's right.

00:13:13.345 --> 00:13:15.578
They've been calling us
the black brothers all morning.

00:13:15.578 --> 00:13:18.001
Jojo's got black head to toe and me too.

00:13:18.266 --> 00:13:19.526
-I'll take your hand-me-down.

00:13:19.526 --> 00:13:21.642
I'm telling you, man, you better be glad,

00:13:21.642 --> 00:13:23.082
'cause he knows I don't play that.

00:13:23.082 --> 00:13:26.435
If my knee wasn't hurting, man,
I'd be smoking your a** right now.

00:13:26.435 --> 00:13:28.505
[Peter] You wanna race? I'll race you.

00:13:28.505 --> 00:13:30.270
I'll race you right now.

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:32.385
-Let's do it.
-I'll hold the camera.

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:34.451
Peter's gonna represent me.

00:13:34.451 --> 00:13:37.186
-[Peter] I haven't run forever.
-I don't wanna hear it!

00:13:37.186 --> 00:13:39.457
-[laughter]
-[Peter] Why are you running away from me?

00:13:39.457 --> 00:13:42.070
-No, he's lining up.
Cigarette in his head, Peter.

00:13:42.071 --> 00:13:45.737
This has got to go down. It'll be beautiful
if you beat him with your cigarette.

00:13:45.737 --> 00:13:47.408
Let's get down here.

00:13:47.408 --> 00:13:48.923
From the pole, Peter.

00:13:48.923 --> 00:13:50.440
-We'll go to the pole and race here.

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:52.952
[JoJo] 66 years old, Michael Holmes.

00:13:53.348 --> 00:13:55.596
-Umar. The Mighty Umar.
-The Mighty Umar.

00:13:55.596 --> 00:13:59.000
Oh, my God.
This is about to be bad, Peter, if you lose

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:02.473
to this old-a** man. [giggles]

00:14:03.610 --> 00:14:05.603
Hey, the ambulance is that way, okay?

00:14:05.824 --> 00:14:07.962
[Peter] Where's the finish line?

00:14:08.130 --> 00:14:10.650
-To me… Peter.
-So we're doing a short sprint?

00:14:11.273 --> 00:14:13.105
-I'm 66. I can't do no mile.

00:14:13.647 --> 00:14:15.320
How old are you, Peter?

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:16.491
-I haven't run in years.

00:14:16.492 --> 00:14:19.937
Yeah, you gotta do it with the stick.
Okay, what are you do? A three, two, one?

00:14:19.937 --> 00:14:21.585
-Yeah, Peter, you end up on this side.

00:14:21.585 --> 00:14:23.085
Mike, you end up on this side.

00:14:23.472 --> 00:14:24.472
On go.

00:14:25.299 --> 00:14:27.339
Ready, set, go!

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:29.240
Oh, my God.

00:14:29.723 --> 00:14:32.587
-Come on! Aah!
-Oh, my God!

00:14:32.587 --> 00:14:34.920
[JoJo laughs]

00:14:36.101 --> 00:14:37.475
Man, you had him though.

00:14:37.475 --> 00:14:38.686
I threw a rod!

00:14:39.869 --> 00:14:40.869
All right, Peter.

00:14:41.889 --> 00:14:44.320
[JoJo] And see this is how
gentrification happens. [laughs]

00:14:48.403 --> 00:14:50.329
Hey, I was impressed for the moment, man.

00:14:50.329 --> 00:14:51.742
You had me for a bit.

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:57.300
With a cigarette in his hand.
Racing in my behalf at this point.

00:14:57.300 --> 00:14:59.022
-Yeah, that was for JoJo.

00:14:59.022 --> 00:15:01.766
-Peter. You blew my dog gone rod.
-That was good.

00:15:02.326 --> 00:15:05.287
We'll try next year, huh?
You threw my rod.

00:15:05.605 --> 00:15:07.512
Oh, you want to race me again when I'm 67?

00:15:07.513 --> 00:15:08.863
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
[laughter]

00:15:10.872 --> 00:15:12.472
That was fun, JoJo.

00:15:12.912 --> 00:15:16.048
So we go to your mom and house,
and then I think we get into downtown.

00:15:16.048 --> 00:15:18.828
I feel like I could make
a whole video out here all day.

00:15:18.828 --> 00:15:20.028
This is interesting.

00:15:20.028 --> 00:15:23.096
It's cool hanging out with
the guys you grew up with, right?

00:15:23.096 --> 00:15:25.930
What's good is
I have to show my face around here.

00:15:25.930 --> 00:15:28.580
And people a lot of times
recognize you from your car.

00:15:29.028 --> 00:15:31.363
-I'm using Hunchman's car today.
-Your buddy's car.

00:15:31.363 --> 00:15:33.405
Well, I crashed my car
and then I got another

00:15:33.405 --> 00:15:35.595
and I don't know,
the engine like went on it.

00:15:36.165 --> 00:15:37.682
People will like…

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.720
"Oh man, JoJo, you don't come by
and you don't say hello."

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:42.330
We don't see you anymore.

00:15:42.675 --> 00:15:44.530
And they will disown you, you know?

00:15:45.011 --> 00:15:46.851
Because you made it big time.

00:15:46.852 --> 00:15:47.852
Right, right.

00:15:47.852 --> 00:15:50.239
So I'm sure there's always envy, right?

00:15:50.239 --> 00:15:52.900
Yeah, they expect you
to come and give money.

00:15:52.900 --> 00:15:55.420
I was never rich.
I never made a lot of money.

00:15:55.968 --> 00:15:57.543
In the NFL, you didn't make money?

00:15:57.543 --> 00:15:59.696
No, I mean, I made the league minimum.

00:15:59.697 --> 00:16:01.977
You know, and again, this was 1995.

00:16:02.486 --> 00:16:05.521
-Okay.
-So today that money is like, you know…

00:16:05.521 --> 00:16:08.136
-Short lived, right?
-Absolutely, absolutely.

00:16:08.136 --> 00:16:11.307
So a lot of these football players
go broke, right? I've heard of that.

00:16:11.307 --> 00:16:12.307
Absolutely.

00:16:12.307 --> 00:16:14.614
'Cause what's the average season?
Like four or five years?

00:16:14.614 --> 00:16:17.361
Man, you want to put on this show
that you have money

00:16:17.361 --> 00:16:19.635
and you buy a car that you can't afford.

00:16:19.636 --> 00:16:21.215
-Right.
-And I'll never forget.

00:16:21.215 --> 00:16:23.712
this guy Ray Lee Johnson
at the San Diego Chargers.

00:16:23.712 --> 00:16:27.979
He was my locker next to me
and his agent comes in,

00:16:28.263 --> 00:16:32.265
"Ray Lee, good news, man.
You made a million dollars last year.

00:16:32.638 --> 00:16:35.109
So the bad news is you spent 1.2."

00:16:35.110 --> 00:16:37.224
So it's like his first year in the NFL

00:16:37.224 --> 00:16:39.178
and he's $200,000 in the hole.

00:16:39.884 --> 00:16:41.762
He lost money by going to the NFL.

00:16:41.762 --> 00:16:43.208
-Absolutely.
-Wow.

00:16:43.423 --> 00:16:45.760
-So there's a lot of that happening?
-Yeah.

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:49.171
Doesn't the NFL have some sort of guidance,
like some financial consultant

00:16:49.171 --> 00:16:51.941
that jumps in in the early career
to be like, hey…

00:16:51.941 --> 00:16:54.568
They'll advise you,
but you don't really get a pension

00:16:54.568 --> 00:16:56.242
unless you've played four years.

00:16:56.809 --> 00:17:00.002
And a lot of guys don't get there,
especially running backs.

00:17:00.476 --> 00:17:01.835
Most people get injured.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:05.590
-So this is the house you grew up in?
-Yes.

00:17:05.590 --> 00:17:09.325
My aunt owned this house and I bought it
from her recently over the years.

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:12.440
We're going to meet JoJo's mother,

00:17:13.124 --> 00:17:15.589
who I believe grew up in Savannah.

00:17:15.589 --> 00:17:17.024
She's got some old stories.

00:17:17.836 --> 00:17:19.629
So it all started here, JoJo?

00:17:19.899 --> 00:17:20.770
-Yes.

00:17:20.770 --> 00:17:22.760
-What's the dog's name?
-Jax.

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:25.060
-Jax.
-Jax is a mini-doodle.

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:27.565
She wasn't supposed to even get that big.

00:17:28.605 --> 00:17:29.605
-She's a cutie.

00:17:30.843 --> 00:17:32.399
This is my mom and my dad's

00:17:32.954 --> 00:17:35.731
picture back in the day before all of us.

00:17:36.090 --> 00:17:38.572
This is my son Jagger, my daughter Axel.

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:40.533
Look at this artistry I got in Ghana.

00:17:41.139 --> 00:17:42.512
I spent like 10 bucks for it.

00:17:42.939 --> 00:17:44.787
-That's cool.
-[Jax barking]

00:17:44.787 --> 00:17:46.832
Hey Jax, nobody's gonna record you.

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:51.584
[Peter] I just did
a running race on JoJo's behalf.

00:17:51.951 --> 00:17:53.251
-Guess who he raced, mama?

00:17:53.571 --> 00:17:54.679
-I raced.

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:55.880
Remember Michael Holmes?

00:17:56.309 --> 00:18:00.359
He was on camera telling Peter
that he used to have a crush on you.

00:18:00.732 --> 00:18:01.758
[laughter]

00:18:01.758 --> 00:18:04.118
-He had a crush on you,
then he said he wanted to race,

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:05.912
and then I raced him.

00:18:05.913 --> 00:18:07.413
Peter ends up racing the guy.

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:10.559
He's 66. He's 12 years younger.

00:18:10.560 --> 00:18:11.560
Yeah.

00:18:11.887 --> 00:18:13.426
You're styling. You're styling.

00:18:13.426 --> 00:18:15.382
I mean, it's understandable.

00:18:15.902 --> 00:18:17.686
-How you feeling?
-Hey, how are you?

00:18:18.630 --> 00:18:20.490
[Peter] Okay, so you have deep roots here?

00:18:20.490 --> 00:18:23.182
Yeah, because basically this was

00:18:23.182 --> 00:18:26.042
more the African American community

00:18:26.042 --> 00:18:28.944
back to like the 1880s than even before.

00:18:29.573 --> 00:18:31.806
But it's odd in a way,
it was a mixed neighborhood

00:18:32.408 --> 00:18:35.087
of Jewish and African American people.

00:18:35.302 --> 00:18:36.302
-Did you guys get along?

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:37.780
Yeah, yeah.

00:18:38.455 --> 00:18:40.653
A lot of the Jewish were tradesmen.

00:18:41.346 --> 00:18:44.179
They had stores. And many of them,

00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:47.167
I guess just starting out,
they lived above their stores.

00:18:47.667 --> 00:18:49.490
So they were like little grocery stores.

00:18:49.490 --> 00:18:51.820
-So that's what it was around here?
-Mm-hmm.

00:18:51.820 --> 00:18:56.417
And then you did have your other
smaller Black businesses, mechanics.

00:18:56.417 --> 00:18:59.079
So what you saw here were professionals,

00:19:00.029 --> 00:19:02.817
teachers, doctors, lawyers,

00:19:03.313 --> 00:19:04.560
tradesmen,

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:05.940
contractors.

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.890
There were three
Black Catholic parishes during integration.

00:19:09.310 --> 00:19:12.126
It was known as
the most integrated city

00:19:12.607 --> 00:19:15.517
because you could have
a street like this that was all White,

00:19:16.008 --> 00:19:18.205
but in the lanes lived Black peoples.

00:19:18.636 --> 00:19:20.908
So it was like White, Black,
White, Black, White, Black.

00:19:21.630 --> 00:19:24.555
The Charity Hospital was the first hospital

00:19:24.555 --> 00:19:26.462
where Black doctors could practice.

00:19:26.830 --> 00:19:29.180
This was, again,
around the turn of the century.

00:19:29.722 --> 00:19:31.403
Two African American doctors

00:19:31.801 --> 00:19:34.689
came to Savannah, started a nursing school

00:19:35.255 --> 00:19:37.475
that eventually became a hospital.

00:19:37.889 --> 00:19:39.358
There was a hospital,

00:19:39.898 --> 00:19:41.072
Georgia Infirmary,

00:19:41.377 --> 00:19:42.800
where Black people could go,

00:19:43.175 --> 00:19:45.590
but Black doctors
could not come in and practice.

00:19:45.950 --> 00:19:49.500
How do you feel race relations are now
White and Black here in the city?

00:19:51.075 --> 00:19:52.075
I…

00:19:52.373 --> 00:19:54.324
I don't think it's as good as it was.

00:19:54.324 --> 00:19:55.369
-Really?
-Yeah.

00:19:55.369 --> 00:19:57.997
When was it the best,
do you think, in your lifetime?

00:19:57.997 --> 00:20:01.177
I think when everyone
had an understanding of who was who.

00:20:01.893 --> 00:20:04.110
Okay. What years would those be, though?

00:20:04.488 --> 00:20:05.488
I would say…

00:20:06.900 --> 00:20:08.491
maybe up to…

00:20:09.418 --> 00:20:10.418
maybe '70.

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:13.700
-'70s, okay, interesting.
-Yeah.

00:20:15.110 --> 00:20:18.774
And see, this street ran
like five more houses on this block.

00:20:18.992 --> 00:20:19.992
Okay.

00:20:19.992 --> 00:20:21.491
They built this expressway

00:20:22.215 --> 00:20:24.892
and basically built it
straight through the neighborhood.

00:20:24.892 --> 00:20:27.023
It took like five houses,

00:20:27.333 --> 00:20:31.889
went through 37th Street,
which was family homes, professionals.

00:20:31.889 --> 00:20:33.862
And so you could sit on the porch

00:20:34.760 --> 00:20:38.441
and see the kids come
from the smaller rural towns,

00:20:38.686 --> 00:20:40.756
come down 16,

00:20:41.650 --> 00:20:43.177
hit the corner up here,

00:20:43.593 --> 00:20:45.880
and you could see them
go back up in ten minutes.

00:20:45.880 --> 00:20:50.006
They started coming into
the community to buy drugs.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:52.340
And…

00:20:52.684 --> 00:20:53.548
-Okay.

00:20:53.548 --> 00:20:55.948
And what's it like now,
from all your years here?

00:20:56.717 --> 00:20:59.326
Well, in the big drug era,

00:20:59.685 --> 00:21:02.045
you see the big cars and the jewelry.

00:21:02.830 --> 00:21:04.004
Now it's more about

00:21:04.881 --> 00:21:06.923
violence and gangs.

00:21:07.663 --> 00:21:10.072
You shoot at me on this side of town,

00:21:10.072 --> 00:21:12.948
then I'll go on the east side of town
and I'll shoot you.

00:21:12.948 --> 00:21:15.890
And this is a very neighborhood city.

00:21:16.404 --> 00:21:19.178
So you're from West Savannah,
you're from Cuyler-Brownsville,

00:21:19.178 --> 00:21:20.758
you're from the East Side.

00:21:20.759 --> 00:21:22.750
-Okay.
-You know, that kind of thing.

00:21:22.750 --> 00:21:26.291
But then it really came in
and destroyed the neighborhood.

00:21:27.411 --> 00:21:30.571
But the city of Savannah,
they worked very hard.

00:21:30.571 --> 00:21:32.430
They worked very hard with their citizens.

00:21:32.430 --> 00:21:35.139
-You see these style of houses here.
-Mm-hmm.

00:21:35.139 --> 00:21:36.639
There was a big production of

00:21:37.580 --> 00:21:40.603
bringing in homes that people could buy.

00:21:40.603 --> 00:21:42.475
You know, that's a big conversation now.

00:21:42.476 --> 00:21:44.444
-Okay.
-About corporate folks.

00:21:44.826 --> 00:21:45.506
Yeah.

00:21:45.506 --> 00:21:48.067
You know, coming in
buying 20 or 30 houses at a time.

00:21:49.010 --> 00:21:51.206
And so, we're dispersed.

00:21:52.111 --> 00:21:53.160
Right.

00:21:53.160 --> 00:21:55.874
So everyone's got a price
with their house too.

00:21:56.487 --> 00:21:59.983
If someone gave you $5 million,
you're moving tomorrow, right?

00:22:00.443 --> 00:22:01.223
Yeah.

00:22:01.223 --> 00:22:02.828
And when they call me, they call me.

00:22:02.829 --> 00:22:03.751
They do call you?

00:22:03.751 --> 00:22:05.693
Oh, every day, all day long.

00:22:05.693 --> 00:22:07.681
-Seriously? Really?
-10:00 at night.

00:22:07.681 --> 00:22:08.974
Can we go back?

00:22:09.625 --> 00:22:11.593
All the neighbors talk about it.

00:22:11.824 --> 00:22:13.195
What are they offering right now?

00:22:13.195 --> 00:22:14.826
No, they ask me what I want.

00:22:14.827 --> 00:22:16.692
So I'll say $500,000.

00:22:16.692 --> 00:22:18.242
Then they'll hang up. [giggles]

00:22:18.913 --> 00:22:23.611
But there are houses in the neighborhood
that are worth close to a million.

00:22:23.611 --> 00:22:24.310
-Okay.

00:22:24.310 --> 00:22:25.942
But it's like the same style house.

00:22:25.943 --> 00:22:27.989
They just go in, clean them up.

00:22:27.989 --> 00:22:28.770
Yeah.

00:22:28.770 --> 00:22:31.081
How you doing? Good. Do you live here?

00:22:31.834 --> 00:22:35.224
No, I lived here for a while,
but not anymore.

00:22:35.224 --> 00:22:36.140
-Okay. Peter.

00:22:36.140 --> 00:22:38.624
-Jeremy, Nice to meet you.
-Nice to meet you.

00:22:38.624 --> 00:22:39.953
How you doing, young man?

00:22:40.993 --> 00:22:44.166
-Thank you. She styles, huh?
-I know, right?

00:22:44.166 --> 00:22:46.292
I love it. What's that type of hat called?

00:22:47.236 --> 00:22:48.930
This is like a hat from the '30s.

00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:50.474
This is like a cloche.

00:22:50.475 --> 00:22:52.508
A French word, C-L-O-C-H-E?

00:22:53.062 --> 00:22:55.563
The men wear like a baller hat,
I think it was called.

00:22:55.563 --> 00:22:57.110
-Bowler.
-Bowler. Yeah.

00:22:57.110 --> 00:23:00.362
You're saying church attendance is down.
I can see that here.

00:23:00.362 --> 00:23:03.725
Well, it was a Catholic church
for 100 years.

00:23:04.050 --> 00:23:06.883
Like with all churches,
the population is diminishing.

00:23:07.627 --> 00:23:10.957
So they joined this church
with a church in another neighborhood.

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:14.667
They sold it a few years ago
to a Baptist congregation.

00:23:15.109 --> 00:23:16.953
And they stayed there as
long as they could,

00:23:16.953 --> 00:23:18.253
but COVID really killed it

00:23:18.972 --> 00:23:20.422
with people coming, you know,

00:23:20.765 --> 00:23:21.865
or not coming, rather.

00:23:22.322 --> 00:23:24.447
And now it is owned by Muslims.

00:23:24.889 --> 00:23:25.889
So…

00:23:26.122 --> 00:23:28.289
-It's going to turn into a mosque?

00:23:28.745 --> 00:23:29.982
I doubt. I don't know.

00:23:30.590 --> 00:23:33.746
It's only been, what,
four or five months? Yeah.

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:35.290
The Spanish

00:23:35.758 --> 00:23:39.789
started coming into this country
before Savannah English.

00:23:40.390 --> 00:23:44.082
So Savannah was put in place
to stop the Spanish at the border.

00:23:44.082 --> 00:23:46.032
-Coming up from Florida?
-Coming up from Florida.

00:23:46.032 --> 00:23:48.994
Like there are areas going south in Georgia

00:23:49.334 --> 00:23:50.909
that are called St. Mary's.

00:23:51.404 --> 00:23:55.155
They have more, you know,
Roman language names.

00:23:55.689 --> 00:23:57.338
So General Oglethorpe came

00:23:58.255 --> 00:24:01.034
and he was assigned to here.

00:24:01.358 --> 00:24:05.153
And he brought people
from the debtor's prisons in England.

00:24:05.153 --> 00:24:07.092
-You know what debtor's prisons are?
-No.

00:24:08.120 --> 00:24:09.723
You know, there was a time that

00:24:11.156 --> 00:24:13.334
if you couldn't pay your debts,
they'd put you in jail.

00:24:13.334 --> 00:24:16.150
-Oh, okay. Debtor prison. Got you.
-Yeah.

00:24:16.150 --> 00:24:18.447
-That's how it started? One of the reasons?
-Yeah.

00:24:18.447 --> 00:24:19.463
Okay.

00:24:19.463 --> 00:24:22.205
And they came in, made friends with the

00:24:22.559 --> 00:24:25.481
Yamacraw Indians that lived at the river.

00:24:25.481 --> 00:24:26.233
Yeah.

00:24:26.233 --> 00:24:28.242
Yamacraws are basically Cherokees.

00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:31.933
What was this, the first laid out city
in the United States?

00:24:31.933 --> 00:24:34.491
-It's a master design. Master plan.
-Yeah.

00:24:34.491 --> 00:24:36.816
-Yeah, the square.
-And with a lot of parks.

00:24:36.816 --> 00:24:40.886
-A lot of little squares and parks.
-But it was mostly for protection.

00:24:40.886 --> 00:24:43.550
-Military protection. Yeah.
-Oh, that's the reason.

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:47.360
You used to see a lot of the Indigenous
people, but you don't see them

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:49.006
like you used to before.

00:24:49.673 --> 00:24:51.870
The Ogeechee Road is where

00:24:52.229 --> 00:24:55.960
the Cherokee and the Yamacraws,
where you see these folks going,

00:24:55.960 --> 00:24:58.481
ran from the Ogeechee River
to the Savannah River.

00:24:58.481 --> 00:24:59.531
So they would walk it

00:25:00.334 --> 00:25:02.849
from one part of the area

00:25:03.370 --> 00:25:04.470
to the Savannah River.

00:25:05.003 --> 00:25:06.701
So you'll find people that are

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:09.310
you name it, we got it.

00:25:09.848 --> 00:25:12.812
Like myself, I'm probably Cherokee, French,

00:25:13.227 --> 00:25:17.111
Scottish, of course African American,
Irish, you know.

00:25:17.111 --> 00:25:18.975
-Cherokee, French, Scottish?

00:25:18.975 --> 00:25:20.918
-African American.
-Yeah.

00:25:21.240 --> 00:25:23.020
It's a mix of my mom and dad's family.

00:25:23.021 --> 00:25:24.539
-Wow. That's a mix.

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:26.694
[siren blares in the distance]

00:25:31.626 --> 00:25:34.587
This is a house that I rent,
usually to people that I know.

00:25:34.946 --> 00:25:37.641
Usually that are people
that can't get a lease anywhere.

00:25:37.895 --> 00:25:39.910
A lot of times, Peter, too,

00:25:39.910 --> 00:25:43.191
my friends and family
that are, like, been in jail.

00:25:43.191 --> 00:25:45.563
One of the hardest things to do
is to find a place to stay,

00:25:45.563 --> 00:25:48.006
to find a lease,
to find somebody that will

00:25:48.439 --> 00:25:51.423
trust you to rent.

00:25:52.058 --> 00:25:53.571
This was my office at some point.

00:25:53.572 --> 00:25:55.172
Recently I had to bring a bed in

00:25:55.763 --> 00:25:57.693
for someone to have a place to stay.

00:25:58.198 --> 00:25:59.598
This is my wall of fame, man.

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:03.180
My sister made this, created this
for me some years ago.

00:26:03.563 --> 00:26:05.779
-There you are in the Chargers Jersey.
-Yeah, man.

00:26:05.779 --> 00:26:08.315
I'll never forget that play.
I hurt my shoulder or whatever.

00:26:08.315 --> 00:26:11.939
But this is my team in Northern Italy,
in Trieste, Italy.

00:26:11.939 --> 00:26:13.078
-Oh, that's cool.

00:26:13.078 --> 00:26:15.116
-This is me coaching in Holland.

00:26:15.585 --> 00:26:16.985
This is me playing in Italy.

00:26:17.616 --> 00:26:19.807
This is one of the other
running backs at the Chargers.

00:26:19.807 --> 00:26:21.492
Look how much bigger
he was than I am.

00:26:22.630 --> 00:26:26.119
This is an interview
that I did with them just saying

00:26:26.119 --> 00:26:28.519
how impossible for me
to make it through the NFL.

00:26:29.743 --> 00:26:32.523
[announcer] …the wide receiver
and the quarterback.

00:26:33.785 --> 00:26:35.125
Joe, Joe Jones.

00:26:35.869 --> 00:26:38.771
[John Madden] I went to practice
and I watched him down in training camp.

00:26:38.771 --> 00:26:41.300
He was the star of the practice.
They couldn't touch him.

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:44.741
He broke Walter Payton's NAIA record.

00:26:44.741 --> 00:26:46.811
Walter Payton had 66. He had 68.

00:26:47.350 --> 00:26:51.020
This is the article where I broke
Walter Payton's all-time touchdown record.

00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:52.312
-Seriously?
-Yeah. Yeah.

00:26:52.313 --> 00:26:55.380
He held the record for like 20 years.
I ended up breaking it.

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:57.889
This is my autographed picture
from Walter Payton.

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:01.064
He calls me and I go,
this ain't no damn Walter Payton.

00:27:01.064 --> 00:27:02.264
And I hang up the phone.

00:27:02.559 --> 00:27:04.578
He calls me right back. It was pretty cool.

00:27:04.578 --> 00:27:07.009
How was that getting on the Chargers?

00:27:07.010 --> 00:27:08.271
What was that feeling like?

00:27:08.271 --> 00:27:10.912
It was surreal. It really was like…

00:27:11.540 --> 00:27:14.848
Again, even when they called and said,
"Hey, we got an airline ticket for you."

00:27:14.848 --> 00:27:16.796
I thought it was one of my college buddies.

00:27:16.797 --> 00:27:18.947
"Hey, it's the Tampa Bay Jalopies.

00:27:18.947 --> 00:27:22.003
We want you to hike the ball
and kick it at the same time."

00:27:22.004 --> 00:27:24.048
They were just pranking me and whatnot.

00:27:24.048 --> 00:27:28.735
And I just thought it wasn't real
until I actually got there. You know?

00:27:28.915 --> 00:27:29.709
-Wow.

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:31.449
This is me playing in Austria.

00:27:31.810 --> 00:27:33.670
Playing in Europe
was probably the best for me

00:27:33.670 --> 00:27:35.865
because it wasn't
so much pressure and stress.

00:27:36.300 --> 00:27:39.520
Again, you could tell how much
smaller I was than everyone else.

00:27:39.520 --> 00:27:42.730
But playing in Europe just allowed me
to have fun playing football again.

00:27:42.730 --> 00:27:45.956
-The NFL life is very stressful, right?
-Yes. It's a business.

00:27:45.956 --> 00:27:47.897
'Cause you're on
the chopping block at all times.

00:27:47.897 --> 00:27:49.773
-Any time.
-If you don't perform, then…

00:27:49.773 --> 00:27:51.690
-There you go. You're out of there.
-You're out.

00:27:51.690 --> 00:27:52.865
You are out of there.

00:27:52.865 --> 00:27:53.865
This is my mini-me.

00:27:54.384 --> 00:27:56.940
We make life-like figurines of real people.

00:27:56.940 --> 00:27:59.530
-No way. So someone orders one
of these and they…

00:27:59.530 --> 00:28:01.033
-Yeah.
-How do they do it?

00:28:01.034 --> 00:28:03.378
Go to www.3Dwithatwist.com

00:28:03.778 --> 00:28:07.050
and it's a little bit more expensive
when you can't be there in person.

00:28:07.050 --> 00:28:09.304
But we do a 360 video view

00:28:09.304 --> 00:28:11.767
or you can do it with your iPhone.

00:28:11.767 --> 00:28:12.414
-Okay.

00:28:12.415 --> 00:28:16.930
And we take a front, back,
side to side, of your closest pictures,

00:28:17.272 --> 00:28:19.930
and you send that to us and 10 to 12 days

00:28:20.380 --> 00:28:23.051
right at your doorstep. Without a doubt.

00:28:23.051 --> 00:28:25.448
And all from a former NFL player.

00:28:25.449 --> 00:28:26.649
There you go. [chuckles]

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:30.996
-So it's not all perhaps
what it's cracked up to be for everyone.

00:28:30.996 --> 00:28:33.054
It's a lot of pressure, lot of stress.

00:28:33.054 --> 00:28:35.080
Yeah. You know,
somebody said to me the other day,

00:28:35.080 --> 00:28:38.057
and that's just life in general, man,
life keeps lifing, you know?

00:28:38.058 --> 00:28:41.524
And you even mentioned like, man,
I've been broke a few times in my life.

00:28:41.524 --> 00:28:44.211
-Sure.
-I think that's good for people to hear.

00:28:44.211 --> 00:28:46.840
Because today with our young kids,
there's so much stress

00:28:46.840 --> 00:28:50.731
about making money,
and being successful, and driving this car.

00:28:50.959 --> 00:28:53.896
That's… I'll be the first person
to tell anyone, man,

00:28:53.896 --> 00:28:57.831
the saddest times of my life
is when I had the biggest bank account.

00:28:57.831 --> 00:28:59.269
And the happiest times are

00:28:59.611 --> 00:29:02.023
when I was eight years old
and our lights were turned off.

00:29:02.023 --> 00:29:03.558
You know, that's… I just…

00:29:03.559 --> 00:29:06.084
-That's my memory. That's my experience.
-Mm-hmm.

00:29:06.084 --> 00:29:07.117
So…

00:29:07.413 --> 00:29:08.413
Life keeps lifing.

00:29:09.557 --> 00:29:12.177
You never get to a point.
'Cause it's like whack-a-mole.

00:29:12.177 --> 00:29:15.050
You think everything's set up and
something's gonna come out of nowhere.

00:29:15.050 --> 00:29:16.998
Life always continues to happen.

00:29:16.998 --> 00:29:19.665
Something negative
is always going to happen.

00:29:19.960 --> 00:29:23.994
Sometimes our egos get in the way
and a lot of times,

00:29:23.994 --> 00:29:26.667
you know God,
and whoever that power may be will

00:29:26.667 --> 00:29:27.725
sit you down.

00:29:27.725 --> 00:29:29.827
-Right. You can either
learn from it or fight it.

00:29:29.827 --> 00:29:31.977
And if you fight it,
it's going to come at you harder.

00:29:31.977 --> 00:29:34.777
There you go.
You got to change it is what you got to do.

00:29:36.410 --> 00:29:38.160
You know, my dad, he wasn't around.

00:29:39.040 --> 00:29:41.288
He lived like a mile away.

00:29:41.645 --> 00:29:43.045
-But he wasn't around.
-Okay.

00:29:43.442 --> 00:29:45.666
I always kind of get choked up
when I think about this.

00:29:45.666 --> 00:29:47.242
But I had this really, like,

00:29:48.267 --> 00:29:51.147
-harsh feelings about him for a long time.
-I bet.

00:29:51.147 --> 00:29:53.890
And my dad was my football coach.

00:29:53.890 --> 00:29:56.530
He didn't realize what a good
football player I was or whatever,

00:29:56.530 --> 00:29:59.213
But he would take other kids home
and not take me home.

00:29:59.213 --> 00:30:00.650
-You know what I mean?
-Oh, man.

00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:02.353
I went to therapy, you know.

00:30:02.353 --> 00:30:05.543
And if you don't know anything about,
our culture, our community, man.

00:30:05.543 --> 00:30:07.388
-We don't go to therapy.
-You don’t?

00:30:07.388 --> 00:30:09.658
Black people are not known
to go to therapy.

00:30:09.880 --> 00:30:11.526
Talk to your grandmother.
I don't know.

00:30:11.526 --> 00:30:12.895
But I went to therapy, man.

00:30:12.895 --> 00:30:14.945
And this lady puts me in this…

00:30:15.807 --> 00:30:19.066
This cold room and I'm on this chair,
this East Indian girl, you know.

00:30:19.066 --> 00:30:21.543
I'm like, "What does she know?
How's she gonna help me?"

00:30:21.543 --> 00:30:22.993
is what I'm saying to myself.

00:30:23.356 --> 00:30:25.304
And she's, I'm laying there and

00:30:25.781 --> 00:30:28.246
I almost I almost fall asleep.
I thought she hypnotized me,

00:30:28.246 --> 00:30:29.520
but she really didn't.

00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:32.394
And she comes in the room
about 30 minutes later

00:30:32.394 --> 00:30:34.680
and she's just asking me
all these questions.

00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:37.458
And she's like, I think she hypnotized me,

00:30:37.459 --> 00:30:39.000
but I can feel myself, you know.

00:30:39.001 --> 00:30:41.351
She's like, "JoJo, where are you?"
And I'm like,

00:30:42.032 --> 00:30:43.990
"I'm in a field." you know.

00:30:43.990 --> 00:30:46.927
And she's like,
"Where are you more specifically?"

00:30:46.928 --> 00:30:48.328
I said, I'm at Forsyth Park.

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:52.020
She's like, "What are you doing?"
I said, "I'm just standing there."

00:30:52.020 --> 00:30:55.390
She says, "Who's there with you?"
I said, "Nobody." She says, "Look closer."

00:30:55.390 --> 00:30:59.115
And the craziest thing, Peter,
it was my dad there.

00:30:59.787 --> 00:31:03.422
And the reason I knew he was there,
I could smell his Cologne.

00:31:03.715 --> 00:31:06.299
I could smell the jewelry that he wore.

00:31:06.299 --> 00:31:09.099
He wore these green stones
and these medals on his rings.

00:31:09.470 --> 00:31:12.676
I could smell the Jerry curl juice.
You know what I mean?

00:31:12.676 --> 00:31:14.378
All this stuff was there.

00:31:14.846 --> 00:31:16.887
And she's like, what's your dad doing?

00:31:16.887 --> 00:31:21.042
I said, he's talking to people.
He's giving out football instructions.

00:31:21.042 --> 00:31:24.351
And she's like, what else is he doing?
I said, he's ignoring me.

00:31:24.888 --> 00:31:28.221
And I'm like, wow. Kind of teared me up.

00:31:28.696 --> 00:31:29.413
Yeah.

00:31:29.413 --> 00:31:32.660
So afterwards, she asked me
a lot of more questions.

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:35.072
And she goes on to say,

00:31:35.659 --> 00:31:37.520
"How long has your dad
been coaching football?"

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:38.760
I said about 30 years.

00:31:38.760 --> 00:31:41.791
He started this organization
called the Forsyth Flames.

00:31:42.186 --> 00:31:46.358
And so much violence going on in this area.
So anyway…

00:31:46.358 --> 00:31:47.777
-Right now?
-Yeah.

00:31:48.104 --> 00:31:51.303
Recently somebody was shooting
at each other and knocked the wall down.

00:31:51.643 --> 00:31:53.337
-Oh, really?
-Yeah.

00:31:53.637 --> 00:31:56.195
And it's like the third time
they put the wall up

00:31:56.196 --> 00:31:58.637
for somebody knocking it over.

00:31:59.350 --> 00:32:00.427
But anyway,

00:32:01.593 --> 00:32:03.576
she's like, how many times

00:32:04.321 --> 00:32:08.427
after 30 years of your dad coaching
football have people walked up to you

00:32:08.914 --> 00:32:10.886
and said, your dad saved my life?

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:13.493
Or your dad kept me out of prison?

00:32:13.494 --> 00:32:15.343
Or your dad was the reason
I'm a good…

00:32:15.975 --> 00:32:17.285
[sobs] A good father?

00:32:17.285 --> 00:32:19.480
And I said, a thousand times.

00:32:20.127 --> 00:32:23.655
And she said, even if your dad
didn't reach your expectations,

00:32:23.655 --> 00:32:25.330
but look how many other people he helped.

00:32:25.330 --> 00:32:27.737
And that helped me so much, Peter.

00:32:27.737 --> 00:32:29.810
-Oh, really?
-Yeah. Get over that.

00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:32.760
Because, I mean,
I've ruined a lot of good relationships

00:32:33.050 --> 00:32:36.395
because of the way I felt
like my dad treated me.

00:32:36.395 --> 00:32:38.692
Especially when it comes to your wife.

00:32:38.692 --> 00:32:40.607
-You know, that kind of thing.
-Okay.

00:32:40.607 --> 00:32:43.167
So, you know, it always, you know…

00:32:43.168 --> 00:32:44.120
Are you married, JoJo?

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:47.882
No, I was married recently.

00:32:48.382 --> 00:32:50.403
-I'm sorry.
-It's about two years now.

00:32:50.403 --> 00:32:51.403
Recently divorced.

00:32:51.830 --> 00:32:54.069
But, you know, good woman.
The whole nine yards.

00:32:54.400 --> 00:32:56.412
It's always my fault. [chuckles]

00:32:57.172 --> 00:32:58.305
It's always my fault.

00:32:58.305 --> 00:33:00.257
So, this is that park. Okay.

00:33:00.257 --> 00:33:02.812
-Can we go around the park here?
-Absolutely.

00:33:02.812 --> 00:33:07.100
This is the most beautiful park, man,
in the city, without a doubt.

00:33:07.100 --> 00:33:09.480
-Most beautiful park in the city.
-Forsyth Park.

00:33:09.480 --> 00:33:12.480
Until my injury,
I was playing basketball there every day.

00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:15.130
The park is a perfect one mile around.

00:33:15.590 --> 00:33:18.682
And in the heat of the summer,
you're always shaded, you know.

00:33:19.203 --> 00:33:22.062
You'll see the SCAD kids
coming through here all day long,

00:33:22.062 --> 00:33:23.565
back and forth to class.

00:33:23.565 --> 00:33:25.806
-Okay, so it goes student pretty quickly.

00:33:25.806 --> 00:33:27.540
-Yeah, really quickly.
Absolutely.

00:33:27.540 --> 00:33:29.460
This is not that far
from your neighborhood.

00:33:29.460 --> 00:33:31.893
No, everything is within proximity, man.

00:33:31.893 --> 00:33:33.323
-Totally changes.
-Yeah.

00:33:34.180 --> 00:33:37.109
[JoJo] And they go out of their way
to make sure the park is kept

00:33:37.109 --> 00:33:38.357
up to par and…

00:33:38.357 --> 00:33:39.580
-Yeah, this is nice.

00:33:39.922 --> 00:33:42.322
So, that's crazy. I mean,
that wall that just got

00:33:42.828 --> 00:33:45.268
shot down multiple times

00:33:45.460 --> 00:33:48.026
is literally a half mile from this.

00:33:48.026 --> 00:33:48.823
-Yep.

00:33:49.126 --> 00:33:52.446
-You see that tree? Is that crazy or what?
-Oh, that tree is stunning.

00:33:52.446 --> 00:33:54.937
-Look at that beauty.
-Looks like something out of Avatar, man.

00:33:54.937 --> 00:33:55.937
Yeah.

00:33:56.730 --> 00:34:00.278
So, like all my videos, when I'm meeting
with someone to show their city,

00:34:00.278 --> 00:34:01.881
I'm going through their perspective.

00:34:01.881 --> 00:34:05.531
I'll push back on questions. I try to get
as much information as possible.

00:34:05.970 --> 00:34:09.540
So, do you feel like it's a consensus
with this SCAD topic?

00:34:09.540 --> 00:34:11.382
I'm sure you talk to other people,
they love it

00:34:11.382 --> 00:34:15.245
because it's brought so much amazingness
to the city too, right? Or like…

00:34:15.750 --> 00:34:17.513
-When it comes to Savannah, yes.

00:34:17.513 --> 00:34:20.968
When it comes to the city,
they're the biggest beautifier,

00:34:21.249 --> 00:34:22.899
and they're the biggest adversary.

00:34:23.660 --> 00:34:24.866
This is Jones Street.

00:34:24.866 --> 00:34:27.070
-Is this one of the famous streets?
-Yes.

00:34:27.070 --> 00:34:28.548
Really interesting feel.

00:34:28.548 --> 00:34:30.654
It's like nothing I've experienced before.

00:34:31.163 --> 00:34:34.070
-It's got a little bit of Northeast to it.
-Mm-hmm.

00:34:34.070 --> 00:34:37.274
Like some of these
brick buildings with shutters

00:34:37.275 --> 00:34:39.434
and then you have the oaks.

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:42.939
It's a different world
with a Southern feel.

00:34:42.939 --> 00:34:44.840
-I don't know how to explain it.
-Absolutely.

00:34:44.840 --> 00:34:46.483
This is awesome though.

00:34:47.010 --> 00:34:51.438
[Peter] So you have the college here.
Big art and design and it's well-known.

00:34:51.438 --> 00:34:54.139
It's attracting people
from all over the country and the world.

00:34:54.139 --> 00:34:57.555
You have a lot of tourists coming
for this stuff 'cause it's walkable.

00:34:57.555 --> 00:35:00.838
And then we're going to cruise by it soon,
but I did some research.

00:35:00.838 --> 00:35:04.220
The port here is
one of the biggest ports in the country.

00:35:04.220 --> 00:35:05.420
I had no idea that existed.

00:35:05.420 --> 00:35:07.099
-Yeah.
-Absolutely.

00:35:07.099 --> 00:35:10.313
So you have like these three
sort of pillars of the economy.

00:35:10.313 --> 00:35:11.313
There you go.

00:35:11.313 --> 00:35:13.920
Then a military base
outside of the city somewhere.

00:35:13.920 --> 00:35:16.560
We have Hunter Army Airfield
and we have Hinesville,

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:17.677
then we have Buford.

00:35:17.677 --> 00:35:19.840
So here's the tourist class
most likely, right?

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:21.590
-They look like tourists.
-Yeah.

00:35:21.590 --> 00:35:24.218
I'd look it up. I want to say
it's like the third or the fourth

00:35:24.218 --> 00:35:26.360
most visited city in the country.

00:35:26.360 --> 00:35:28.620
-I didn't know that. This is my first time.
-Yeah.

00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:31.929
I was in Hamburg, Germany,
and this guy was like, Savannah, Georgia.

00:35:32.460 --> 00:35:34.956
It's our dream vacation, me and my wife.

00:35:34.956 --> 00:35:36.130
-Oh, no way.
-Yeah.

00:35:36.130 --> 00:35:39.390
[JoJo] This is a cool area right here.
You're going to want this statue here.

00:35:39.390 --> 00:35:41.854
See, these are Black soldiers
that were getting an opportunity

00:35:41.854 --> 00:35:43.327
to fight in the Confederate War.

00:35:43.327 --> 00:35:45.767
-Right. And a lot of people
don't know that too, right?

00:35:45.767 --> 00:35:47.843
Blacks were fighting
in the Confederate Army.

00:35:48.282 --> 00:35:49.948
-Front line. [chuckles]
-Yeah.

00:35:51.090 --> 00:35:53.195
[JoJo] Man, this dude here
has a great story, man.

00:35:53.195 --> 00:35:56.152
I don't want to kind of put him on blast,
but this guy here, Vernon.

00:35:56.152 --> 00:35:58.620
-Oh, he wants to talk. He was waving.

00:35:58.620 --> 00:36:00.463
Been to prison, changed his life.

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:02.020
Hey, Vernon.

00:36:02.530 --> 00:36:04.780
You want to chat
with JoJo and I for a second?

00:36:04.780 --> 00:36:05.780
[JoJo laughs]

00:36:06.339 --> 00:36:08.400
We'll meet you right up here.

00:36:08.400 --> 00:36:10.220
Oh, man. He's like…

00:36:10.220 --> 00:36:11.220
[laughs]

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:15.093
You saw me backing up so you couldn't see.

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:19.200
-We definitely can chat.
-You thought I was like a cop or something?

00:36:19.201 --> 00:36:20.386
[JoJo] Oh, heck yeah.

00:36:21.260 --> 00:36:23.785
Vernon, JoJo and I
are making a video about Savannah

00:36:23.786 --> 00:36:25.137
getting his take on things.

00:36:25.137 --> 00:36:27.337
He said you're a legend. You're the dude.

00:36:27.337 --> 00:36:29.787
I'm not a legend in Savannah.
I'm from California.

00:36:30.784 --> 00:36:32.623
[laughing] Let me feel your heart.

00:36:33.067 --> 00:36:34.560
"Hey, Vernon." Government?

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:39.261
-Did you think I was a parole officer?
-I'm far removed from that.

00:36:39.261 --> 00:36:42.201
I was just telling him
Vernon's changed his life, man.

00:36:42.201 --> 00:36:44.156
-He said hero story.
-Yeah.

00:36:44.156 --> 00:36:45.130
Do you want to share?

00:36:45.130 --> 00:36:47.792
I always love the hero story.
People that turned their life around.

00:36:47.792 --> 00:36:48.982
Yeah. No problem.

00:36:48.982 --> 00:36:51.659
-Currently, I'm…
-I was looking at that, baby. Okay.

00:36:51.659 --> 00:36:54.425
Currently, I'm just made 25 years.

00:36:54.425 --> 00:36:57.284
Worked for local government.
You know, 49 years old.

00:36:57.830 --> 00:36:59.485
I'm originally from California.

00:36:59.485 --> 00:37:01.135
I joined a gang at the age of 12.

00:37:01.600 --> 00:37:03.266
-[Peter] Wow.
-[JoJo] I didn't know that.

00:37:03.266 --> 00:37:04.498
Bloods? Crips?

00:37:04.498 --> 00:37:07.093
Bloods. In real Blood gang.
San Diego, California.

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:09.921
And from there,
I had a friend named Odie Cat

00:37:10.462 --> 00:37:12.008
that turned me on to PCP.

00:37:12.580 --> 00:37:16.070
And that took me on the spiral
from about 13 to about 17.

00:37:16.070 --> 00:37:17.546
But I come from a good background.

00:37:17.546 --> 00:37:22.236
My mom was an educator,
my father retired at an E-9 in the Navy.

00:37:22.236 --> 00:37:23.252
Okay.

00:37:23.252 --> 00:37:25.002
So that's why we were in San Diego.

00:37:26.420 --> 00:37:28.163
My sister, she was born in Italy,

00:37:28.164 --> 00:37:30.514
so we lived in Naples, Italy
for eight years.

00:37:30.514 --> 00:37:32.366
-That's where my family's from.
-Oh, Naples?

00:37:32.366 --> 00:37:34.473
-Originally, yeah.
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:37:34.473 --> 00:37:37.960
We lived there for eight years and then
we went to Okinawa, Japan for a year.

00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:38.953
Nice.

00:37:38.953 --> 00:37:40.262
Then back to California.

00:37:40.262 --> 00:37:42.907
-And I think what happened was…
-[JoJo] I didn't know none of this.

00:37:42.907 --> 00:37:45.304
Yeah. My mom and my daddy
got a divorce at 12.

00:37:46.070 --> 00:37:48.177
And that was a…

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:50.712
a vital time that I needed them in my life.

00:37:50.712 --> 00:37:51.740
-Yep.

00:37:51.740 --> 00:37:54.010
But he had to do… He had his own journey.

00:37:54.010 --> 00:37:57.810
So with that being said, my mom, she was
a military wife, so she didn't work.

00:37:58.830 --> 00:38:02.760
So when they got a divorce, she had to
try to go back to school, find a job.

00:38:02.760 --> 00:38:04.610
Which left me looking over my sister.

00:38:05.150 --> 00:38:07.500
And I first started out
and met a dude named Duty.

00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:10.675
And Duty was in
an apartment complex called Bay Vista.

00:38:11.260 --> 00:38:13.630
Bay Vista Apartments. Still there.

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:17.658
A famous rapper, his name is Missy Slick.

00:38:17.658 --> 00:38:20.035
He's from that area.
The gang there was Lincoln Park.

00:38:20.035 --> 00:38:22.831
But long story short,
I made my first $50 a day

00:38:22.832 --> 00:38:24.586
by just holding a walkie-talkie,

00:38:25.060 --> 00:38:27.140
when the police come through,
let them know.

00:38:27.140 --> 00:38:28.140
Just scouting?

00:38:29.180 --> 00:38:32.147
And what I learned about gangs…

00:38:32.148 --> 00:38:34.919
Originally gangs were…
the first generation of gangs

00:38:34.919 --> 00:38:36.669
came after the Black Panther Party.

00:38:36.670 --> 00:38:39.020
So once they dismantled
the Black Panther Party,

00:38:39.592 --> 00:38:43.095
they became Bloods and Crips but they were
there just to police the neighborhood.

00:38:43.095 --> 00:38:44.095
[JoJo] That's right.

00:38:44.095 --> 00:38:47.357
Make sure if someone got pulled over
they would just come, stand,

00:38:47.357 --> 00:38:48.957
make sure they weren't harassed.

00:38:49.375 --> 00:38:50.422
But in '85,

00:38:51.065 --> 00:38:52.178
came crack cocaine,

00:38:52.986 --> 00:38:53.986
Reagan era,

00:38:54.286 --> 00:38:56.375
and there were dropping guns
in the neighborhood.

00:38:56.375 --> 00:38:57.630
[JoJo] Mm-hmm. Heard that.

00:38:57.630 --> 00:39:00.430
With that being said,
you got a lot of people in poverty.

00:39:01.605 --> 00:39:03.590
Now it's a way that you can go from

00:39:03.590 --> 00:39:06.429
sleeping on the street
to now being a thousandaire.

00:39:06.709 --> 00:39:07.254
-Yeah.

00:39:07.254 --> 00:39:09.054
If you really hustle, a millionaire.

00:39:10.130 --> 00:39:13.101
But they're not understanding that
you're poisoning your own community.

00:39:13.101 --> 00:39:14.960
-'Cause it's about proximity.
-That's right.

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:16.810
So you feed on what's closest to you.

00:39:17.670 --> 00:39:21.395
What I learned about gangs,
when I went to prison in '97,

00:39:22.015 --> 00:39:24.276
and I got out in '99,
and that's when I moved here.

00:39:24.276 --> 00:39:28.181
But when I was in prison,
I found out it was predator and prey.

00:39:28.950 --> 00:39:30.997
-When I learned that was a lot of…
-Oh, yeah.

00:39:30.997 --> 00:39:33.151
A lot of older gentlemen
who threw their lives away,

00:39:33.828 --> 00:39:37.010
That's impressionable,
because we hearing these stories about you.

00:39:37.010 --> 00:39:38.299
And the hard part is…

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:40.860
'Cause I deal with the youth at my church.

00:39:41.149 --> 00:39:43.525
If you have Mr. Johnson
that lives in the project

00:39:43.525 --> 00:39:46.073
but then you have Earl, the dope man
that lives in the project.

00:39:46.073 --> 00:39:47.830
Mr. Johnson goes to work every day.

00:39:47.830 --> 00:39:48.930
Let's say he works for

00:39:50.368 --> 00:39:51.368
the HOG.

00:39:51.730 --> 00:39:52.893
He's coming home dirty.

00:39:52.893 --> 00:39:54.180
-Port system.
-Port system.

00:39:54.180 --> 00:39:55.180
-Mm-hmm.
-Okay.

00:39:55.180 --> 00:39:56.698
He's coming home dirty,

00:39:57.398 --> 00:40:00.890
but he lives in the same project
that everyone else lives in.

00:40:01.220 --> 00:40:05.061
But Earl, he has the rims,
the cars, the girls respect him.

00:40:05.061 --> 00:40:08.711
Even the elderly people respect him,
because he's maybe paying their rent.

00:40:09.230 --> 00:40:11.300
-He's maybe helping with grocery.
-Okay.

00:40:11.300 --> 00:40:13.120
But once again, predator and prey.

00:40:13.120 --> 00:40:14.630
I paid your rent for a year.

00:40:14.630 --> 00:40:16.020
I have five pounds of weed.

00:40:16.020 --> 00:40:18.304
-I have to leave this in your house.
-[JoJo] That's right.

00:40:18.304 --> 00:40:20.200
Oh, right, right, right.

00:40:20.201 --> 00:40:22.000
So it seems like it's Robin Hood.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.890
-Nothing's for free. Yeah.
-But nothing's for free.

00:40:24.890 --> 00:40:26.450
It's a business model.

00:40:26.450 --> 00:40:27.625
It's like in everything else.

00:40:27.625 --> 00:40:30.210
I don't know if you ever heard of
James Allen, but James Allen

00:40:30.210 --> 00:40:34.156
was the first Black slave in South Carolina
that bought his freedom.

00:40:34.156 --> 00:40:36.225
And then he started a plantation.

00:40:36.225 --> 00:40:40.395
And the legend is,
is that he had worse practices

00:40:40.929 --> 00:40:42.628
than the White slave owners.

00:40:42.628 --> 00:40:44.798
Because he bought into the business model.

00:40:44.798 --> 00:40:45.580
-Right.

00:40:45.580 --> 00:40:47.934
So like today, modern day slavery,

00:40:47.935 --> 00:40:49.235
my name is Vernon Frazier.

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:52.080
But why do I need an employee number?

00:40:54.213 --> 00:40:55.260
Product.

00:40:55.260 --> 00:40:56.380
-What are you doing now?

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:59.185
Right now I'm the manager
of administrative services,

00:40:59.634 --> 00:41:02.960
which in my department,
I have a distribution system,

00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:06.685
supply all packages within the county,
also the mail service.

00:41:06.685 --> 00:41:09.233
So we're kind of like
the United States Postal Service

00:41:09.233 --> 00:41:10.844
for Chatham County in local government.

00:41:10.844 --> 00:41:13.400
-Cool. Honest work though, right?
-Yes, definitely.

00:41:13.400 --> 00:41:15.269
Doesn't that feel different,
doing honest work?

00:41:15.269 --> 00:41:16.480
It's the greatest thing ever.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:18.580
I mean, you're the only judge of yourself.

00:41:19.047 --> 00:41:20.387
-God is.
-There you go.

00:41:20.857 --> 00:41:23.810
-But you can sleep well at night.
-There you go.

00:41:23.810 --> 00:41:26.800
And I'm glad you brought up the Lord.
That's what changed my life.

00:41:26.800 --> 00:41:29.394
When I got out of prison at the end of '98,

00:41:29.394 --> 00:41:31.744
I was on my way here
and I rode a Greyhound bus,

00:41:32.212 --> 00:41:34.078
and I had one layover in El Paso.

00:41:34.415 --> 00:41:36.515
And I remember I had one sherm stick left.

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:39.870
And I went to the bathroom,
and I was going to smoke it but…

00:41:41.440 --> 00:41:44.275
I don't know if you ever felt
the presence of the Holy Spirit

00:41:44.275 --> 00:41:46.615
but in that moment, he rained down on me,

00:41:47.080 --> 00:41:48.863
and I got on my knees, and I told him,

00:41:48.864 --> 00:41:51.580
"If you get me here to Savannah,
it will change my life."

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:54.591
And I got here,
and my mom, she was working at

00:41:55.044 --> 00:41:57.188
Chatham County in state court.

00:41:58.120 --> 00:42:01.570
So they had a second chance program,
which I was able to be a part of.

00:42:02.450 --> 00:42:06.080
And then I just took advantage of it.
So I met this nice guy named Cedric Rouse,

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:08.015
who's my boss now, he's my director.

00:42:08.429 --> 00:42:10.695
And he told me
if I really wanted to change my life

00:42:10.695 --> 00:42:13.676
to come on my lunch break
for three months straight,

00:42:14.050 --> 00:42:16.687
and he'll teach me data entry
and things of that nature.

00:42:16.687 --> 00:42:17.800
I did so.

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:20.400
-So that second chance program
was huge in your life?

00:42:20.670 --> 00:42:23.012
It was the greatest
thing that ever happened.

00:42:23.012 --> 00:42:24.512
Well, the greatest program was

00:42:25.122 --> 00:42:27.172
finding my Lord and Savior, Jesus Christ.

00:42:27.540 --> 00:42:30.903
-A lot of people don't think
they have the power within themselves.

00:42:31.130 --> 00:42:32.971
And so you found God.

00:42:33.180 --> 00:42:36.891
That gave you the ability to see
that you have the power in yourself.

00:42:36.891 --> 00:42:37.689
Yes, sir.

00:42:37.689 --> 00:42:39.489
-But a lot of young people make mistakes.

00:42:39.489 --> 00:42:42.380
They don't think they have the power,
like the agency in their hand

00:42:42.380 --> 00:42:44.130
to make something out of their life.

00:42:44.130 --> 00:42:45.276
Any words for that?

00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:49.056
They need identity and a support system.

00:42:50.090 --> 00:42:52.792
And what I mean
by identity is if all your life

00:42:52.792 --> 00:42:55.542
someone was telling you
you're not going to be anything,

00:42:56.121 --> 00:42:57.889
what does that say to your belief system?

00:42:57.889 --> 00:43:00.532
-There's no way you're going anywhere.

00:43:00.532 --> 00:43:03.177
It's like anything, man.
Words are powerful.

00:43:04.264 --> 00:43:06.387
What you constantly tell yourself,

00:43:07.453 --> 00:43:09.950
your inner speakings with yourself,

00:43:10.658 --> 00:43:11.808
it shapes your reality.

00:43:12.610 --> 00:43:15.369
If you wake up in the morning and say
it's gonna be a horrible day,

00:43:15.369 --> 00:43:17.420
guess what it's going to be?
A horrible day.

00:43:18.251 --> 00:43:20.855
You don't have horrible days,
you may have bad moments.

00:43:20.855 --> 00:43:22.709
What do you do? What's your strategy?

00:43:22.709 --> 00:43:24.448
If you're feeling bad in the morning?

00:43:24.448 --> 00:43:25.448
I journal.

00:43:25.448 --> 00:43:26.448
You journal. Nice.

00:43:26.448 --> 00:43:30.039
So in my journal
I can always look back 2012

00:43:30.039 --> 00:43:32.601
when I thought that day
was the last day of my life.

00:43:32.900 --> 00:43:36.251
and now I'm in 2026 and I say,
hey, if I thought this was it…

00:43:37.371 --> 00:43:39.371
-…this ain't nothing but a stepping stone.
-Right.

00:43:39.372 --> 00:43:42.225
So I'll tell anyone, man,

00:43:42.472 --> 00:43:43.891
every day that you wake up

00:43:44.619 --> 00:43:46.219
just put your best foot forward.

00:43:46.706 --> 00:43:49.285
Don't think about your past.
Don't think about your future.

00:43:49.285 --> 00:43:50.407
Stay in the moment.

00:43:50.407 --> 00:43:53.903
Be present right now at this day and time.

00:43:54.220 --> 00:43:55.220
And love yourself.

00:43:55.805 --> 00:43:59.202
This guy could have easily been me.
I could have easily been him.

00:43:59.202 --> 00:44:01.173
-Yes sir.
-Really though.

00:44:03.100 --> 00:44:05.025
We're probably in San Diego
at the same time.

00:44:05.025 --> 00:44:06.425
That's what I'm telling you.

00:44:09.240 --> 00:44:10.690
[Peter] Downtown Savannah.

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:13.035
Jojo is saying
he's doing his thing for a bit there.

00:44:13.035 --> 00:44:15.335
What it has is a bunch of these squares.

00:44:15.335 --> 00:44:19.409
If you look at Google Maps,
there are a lot of these small squares.

00:44:19.720 --> 00:44:24.100
It'll be like square,
couple of streets, buildings, next square.

00:44:24.700 --> 00:44:27.072
And that was the master design of the city,

00:44:27.596 --> 00:44:29.146
which makes it highly walkable.

00:44:29.860 --> 00:44:31.972
Very much enjoyable to be a tourist in.

00:44:32.920 --> 00:44:36.170
Just one of these places.
So many American cities don't have that.

00:44:36.620 --> 00:44:39.987
Sit on a park bench under a tree
and read a book like this woman.

00:44:40.422 --> 00:44:43.597
But this place definitely has that feel.

00:44:46.161 --> 00:44:47.707
All right.
So where are we off to next?

00:44:47.707 --> 00:44:49.875
-We're going to head
across this light to River Street.

00:44:49.875 --> 00:44:52.940
This is a new nice area.
It kind of puts you in the mind of Vegas.

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:54.990
Like people have never
seen anything like this.

00:44:54.990 --> 00:44:56.587
You know, you've got SCAD here.

00:44:56.587 --> 00:44:57.840
These are all SCAD buildings.

00:44:57.846 --> 00:44:58.846
-Still?
-Yeah.

00:44:59.233 --> 00:45:00.313
Wow.

00:45:00.313 --> 00:45:02.356
-Then you have the projects
right next to it.

00:45:02.356 --> 00:45:03.356
-Really?

00:45:03.356 --> 00:45:06.492
-This guy, Kessler,
this philanthropist, he's rich.

00:45:06.920 --> 00:45:09.360
So he builds these three hotels together.

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:10.975
He calls it the Kessler Collection.

00:45:10.975 --> 00:45:15.020
One has a music theme, one has an
art theme, one has a crystal theme.

00:45:15.430 --> 00:45:17.580
But what's crazy is
it's open to the public.

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:21.231
-These hotels are all new here?
-Yeah.

00:45:21.231 --> 00:45:23.140
Within the last, what, ten years?

00:45:23.140 --> 00:45:24.722
No, like three years.

00:45:24.722 --> 00:45:25.856
-No way.
-Yeah.

00:45:25.856 --> 00:45:27.900
So this river area just came alive.

00:45:27.900 --> 00:45:29.486
-There was nothing here.

00:45:29.486 --> 00:45:31.904
-So growing up,
this was just trashy down here?

00:45:32.451 --> 00:45:33.451
Nothing interesting.

00:45:33.451 --> 00:45:36.194
I think it was gated, you know,
put away or something.

00:45:36.194 --> 00:45:38.103
Look at that crystal.
Oh, there's more?

00:45:38.590 --> 00:45:40.170
-Yeah.
-Oh, wow.

00:45:40.851 --> 00:45:42.600
-This is insane.
-Yes.

00:45:42.915 --> 00:45:44.940
-I've never seen this in a hotel.
-Yeah.

00:45:45.586 --> 00:45:47.960
You've got to see this bar here.
It's called the Baobab.

00:45:47.960 --> 00:45:49.750
It's an African-based bar, right?

00:45:49.750 --> 00:45:51.686
It's exactly like a bar in Ghana.

00:45:52.206 --> 00:45:53.206
Seriously.

00:45:53.630 --> 00:45:54.980
This has to be worth…

00:45:54.980 --> 00:45:58.487
I don't know my crystals, but it's what?
Ten feet tall?

00:45:58.487 --> 00:46:00.086
-Yeah. I've been in this guy's house.

00:46:00.086 --> 00:46:02.317
He has so many of these.

00:46:02.743 --> 00:46:03.743
It makes no sense.

00:46:04.389 --> 00:46:06.146
-The pterodactyl, right?
-Right.

00:46:06.146 --> 00:46:08.563
I'm actually still on
the employee list here.

00:46:08.895 --> 00:46:10.420
-Oh, you worked here?
-Yeah.

00:46:10.420 --> 00:46:12.600
How much is a room a night here, roughly?

00:46:12.600 --> 00:46:14.099
No less than $450 a night.

00:46:14.840 --> 00:46:16.429
Valentine's, $800.

00:46:16.835 --> 00:46:19.135
Wow. Look at this. This is so cool.

00:46:19.587 --> 00:46:21.287
The money to build this thing out.

00:46:21.600 --> 00:46:23.533
I mean, wow.

00:46:24.753 --> 00:46:25.753
Come on in.

00:46:26.752 --> 00:46:27.752
It's crazy, right?

00:46:28.213 --> 00:46:29.213
-Yeah.

00:46:29.970 --> 00:46:31.815
This place is better than a museum.

00:46:31.816 --> 00:46:32.956
It is a museum.

00:46:32.956 --> 00:46:33.956
Right?

00:46:35.070 --> 00:46:38.530
So this town brings in
a lot of tourist dollars, right?

00:46:38.530 --> 00:46:40.230
-A lot of people with money.
-Yeah.

00:46:40.733 --> 00:46:42.506
These are my favorite statues, man.

00:46:42.506 --> 00:46:44.106
They look so real. They're scary.

00:46:45.420 --> 00:46:47.020
[Peter] Got the alligator there.

00:46:47.642 --> 00:46:49.242
[JoJo] Look at that one, though.

00:46:49.428 --> 00:46:50.428
And the bar.

00:46:52.230 --> 00:46:54.980
It took me a long time to realize
that these were whips.

00:46:55.381 --> 00:46:56.600
-They're whips?
-Yeah.

00:46:58.158 --> 00:46:59.658
What was this? An old factory?

00:47:00.533 --> 00:47:03.694
-Perfect question.
It was the electric company for the city.

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:07.187
The coolest place is in here
where they would dump the coal

00:47:07.188 --> 00:47:08.664
to generate the energy.

00:47:09.510 --> 00:47:13.027
So here are the levers that
ran the electricity through the whole city.

00:47:13.027 --> 00:47:15.811
And I don't know how long
this place sat before this guy came in

00:47:15.811 --> 00:47:18.200
and made a deal with the city,
Richard Kessler.

00:47:18.200 --> 00:47:20.770
And what's really cool,
you see him here all the time.

00:47:20.770 --> 00:47:22.395
-The owner?
-Yeah.

00:47:22.810 --> 00:47:24.534
He lives, you know,

00:47:25.456 --> 00:47:26.456
a quarter of a mile away.

00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:29.500
[JoJo] How's it going?

00:47:30.133 --> 00:47:31.033
Good, good, good.

00:47:32.359 --> 00:47:34.059
-[Peter] How are you doing, sir?
-[muffled]

00:47:34.059 --> 00:47:35.323
[Peter] Yeah, thanks.

00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:39.000
You know if that's the famous shot
in New York City or that was here?

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.600
I got the camera that way, not on you.

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:43.858
[man] It's a 3D reproduction
of a 1920s photograph

00:47:43.858 --> 00:47:46.098
of New York City construction workers.

00:47:46.098 --> 00:47:48.345
-Good talking to you.
-Yeah, you too.

00:47:49.008 --> 00:47:51.099
[JoJo] So, Peter,
here's a perfect example.

00:47:51.099 --> 00:47:53.952
Most Black men his age
would never want to do this job.

00:47:53.952 --> 00:47:56.458
They have to because
they don't have another choice,

00:47:56.785 --> 00:47:59.121
but they would never want to do it
but here's the thing,

00:47:59.122 --> 00:48:01.271
He's had a life.
He's had a profession.

00:48:01.525 --> 00:48:05.195
He was a, you know, a photographer,
I'm sure, everywhere around the country.

00:48:05.195 --> 00:48:09.110
So he doesn't mind
because he chooses to do it, I'm sure.

00:48:09.110 --> 00:48:11.119
-Why wouldn't they want to do that?

00:48:11.383 --> 00:48:13.906
Because they've never seen,
they've never had anything.

00:48:13.907 --> 00:48:15.813
It's like you're just a servant.

00:48:16.250 --> 00:48:17.439
That's all you've ever done.

00:48:17.439 --> 00:48:20.130
That's all you've ever had
is to be a slave.

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:23.321
-Yeah, but you're saying
like everyone, not everyone.

00:48:23.321 --> 00:48:25.118
The most of our people, yes.

00:48:25.118 --> 00:48:29.172
There's a small, you know how small
a LeBron James is or an Oprah Winfrey?

00:48:29.437 --> 00:48:30.860
Or Barack Obama?

00:48:30.860 --> 00:48:33.690
I'm talking about
the multitude of people, man.

00:48:34.070 --> 00:48:36.976
They're not enjoying this life.

00:48:37.523 --> 00:48:39.189
They're not enjoying… And I'm…

00:48:39.657 --> 00:48:41.860
I've traveled everywhere
in this world twice.

00:48:41.860 --> 00:48:45.254
And I still understand and I still feel,

00:48:46.068 --> 00:48:49.306
you know, what it feels like to be Black,

00:48:49.313 --> 00:48:51.721
a n*****, a n*****, an African American.

00:48:51.721 --> 00:48:53.100
Why do you say the N-bomb though?

00:48:53.100 --> 00:48:55.747
Because, I mean, it's,
I want to show you this.

00:48:55.747 --> 00:48:56.839
Yeah, let's…

00:48:56.839 --> 00:48:59.499
It's culturally accepted,

00:48:59.880 --> 00:49:02.882
but it's also,
I understand the insult behind it.

00:49:03.189 --> 00:49:04.794
You know what I mean? I don't accept it.

00:49:04.794 --> 00:49:06.160
You know, not everybody can…

00:49:06.161 --> 00:49:09.321
I can say it to myself and people that have
gone through what I've gone through.

00:49:09.321 --> 00:49:12.622
-Yeah, but it's such a bad word. Isn't it?
-[JoJo chuckles] It's a bad word.

00:49:13.050 --> 00:49:15.292
But I just want you to understand
where I'm coming from.

00:49:15.292 --> 00:49:16.160
Okay.

00:49:16.850 --> 00:49:20.866
-I want to show you the coal.
-Oh, this is unbelievable.

00:49:21.380 --> 00:49:24.040
[Peter]
"The Smokestack at Stone and Webster."

00:49:24.040 --> 00:49:26.052
Be open, be open, be open, be open.

00:49:27.392 --> 00:49:28.966
What's this in here, JoJo?

00:49:29.806 --> 00:49:31.026
Secret rooms.

00:49:31.793 --> 00:49:33.093
[JoJo's voice echoes] Aha!

00:49:34.710 --> 00:49:36.910
It's really cool at night
because it's green.

00:49:37.170 --> 00:49:38.170
The lights are green.

00:49:38.170 --> 00:49:40.896
-I like the smell.
It's like fresh concrete.

00:49:40.896 --> 00:49:43.196
-And everything echoes.
-Yeah, it's very clean.

00:49:44.380 --> 00:49:46.247
Talk to me, JoJo, really loud.

00:49:46.247 --> 00:49:47.647
[JoJo's voice echoes] Hello!

00:49:48.195 --> 00:49:49.360
[chuckling]

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:51.802
-Well, my laugh sounds more…
-Woo!

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:55.360
[Peter] So if you're at the steakhouse,
this is your special room.

00:49:55.360 --> 00:49:56.360
-Yeah.

00:50:02.889 --> 00:50:05.080
-What is this?
-Yamacraw Village.

00:50:05.080 --> 00:50:07.310
And you'll immediately know
that it's an Indian name,

00:50:07.310 --> 00:50:08.824
this is Indian land.

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:12.191
-The poorest of the poor live here.
-There are no windows on these places.

00:50:12.191 --> 00:50:13.730
They're boarded off. Why is that?

00:50:13.730 --> 00:50:16.270
-Well, hopefully
nobody's living in there now.

00:50:16.492 --> 00:50:17.210
-Okay.

00:50:17.210 --> 00:50:19.710
-But you'll see the ones
that are without with the blinds.

00:50:19.710 --> 00:50:21.445
See, somebody's living there.

00:50:21.445 --> 00:50:23.618
I was actually with Hashmel,
with the city manager,

00:50:23.618 --> 00:50:27.030
and they're going to do a total
revitalization of this place.

00:50:27.340 --> 00:50:28.840
But you know what that means.

00:50:28.840 --> 00:50:31.855
They're going to make these boutique
high-end apartments.

00:50:32.150 --> 00:50:33.608
One party is saying,

00:50:33.608 --> 00:50:37.107
hey, we want to give the people
an opportunity to move back into them.

00:50:37.440 --> 00:50:39.175
And, of course, the other party is, like,

00:50:39.175 --> 00:50:42.170
we can make a lot more money
by renting to students.

00:50:42.170 --> 00:50:43.630
Is this Section 8 right now?

00:50:43.630 --> 00:50:44.630
Yes, 100%.

00:50:45.010 --> 00:50:48.760
And, you know, you have nothing but
new hotels going up around these places.

00:50:49.310 --> 00:50:51.389
I'm just gonna
be that guy right now, JoJo.

00:50:51.389 --> 00:50:52.389
Please.

00:50:52.389 --> 00:50:55.195
No money comes into town,
no new hotels, no tourists.

00:50:55.910 --> 00:50:57.360
What's the place going to be?

00:50:57.812 --> 00:50:58.812
Um,

00:50:59.343 --> 00:51:00.602
it'd be trash.

00:51:00.602 --> 00:51:02.170
Right, no jobs at the hotels.

00:51:02.170 --> 00:51:03.170
Right, right.

00:51:03.713 --> 00:51:06.650
But… you know, it seems more like…

00:51:09.610 --> 00:51:12.443
Again, that doesn't benefit
my people at all.

00:51:13.010 --> 00:51:16.010
-Okay, when you say your people,
you can't speak for all your people, right?

00:51:16.011 --> 00:51:17.040
-Um…

00:51:17.040 --> 00:51:19.351
-Like, if I speak for me,
I don't say my people.

00:51:19.351 --> 00:51:21.589
All the Whites feel the same as I do,
'cause they don't.

00:51:21.589 --> 00:51:25.389
Well, when I say my people,
I definitely mean the majority.

00:51:25.389 --> 00:51:26.020
Okay.

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:27.752
See the people that are catching the buses?

00:51:27.752 --> 00:51:30.240
See the people that are
living paycheck to paycheck?

00:51:30.240 --> 00:51:32.572
Blacks, Hispanics, Native Americans.

00:51:33.210 --> 00:51:35.690
A lot of Whites, too, JoJo.
You got to understand that.

00:51:35.690 --> 00:51:38.709
More Whites living paycheck
to paycheck than anyone else,

00:51:38.709 --> 00:51:39.925
because there's more of them.

00:51:39.925 --> 00:51:42.035
-But if we ride by here again…
-Yeah.

00:51:42.336 --> 00:51:44.350
-You know what I mean?
-I gotcha.

00:51:44.350 --> 00:51:45.800
That's what we're going to see.

00:51:45.800 --> 00:51:48.750
-Right, and in the hotel,
the guests were mostly White.

00:51:48.750 --> 00:51:52.780
Yeah, and they're doing well, and
the people that are picking up the bags,

00:51:52.780 --> 00:51:55.466
the people that are cooking
and scraping the plates.

00:51:56.220 --> 00:51:58.204
And they'll go,
"Oh, we're all here together."

00:51:58.204 --> 00:52:00.804
Yeah, we are but no one's flourishing.

00:52:00.804 --> 00:52:04.381
No one's having a good time,
except the people that are in power.

00:52:05.120 --> 00:52:06.638
-So the crazy thing is,

00:52:06.639 --> 00:52:09.118
this is right around the corner
from that section 8.

00:52:09.118 --> 00:52:09.715
Yeah.

00:52:09.715 --> 00:52:12.310
Like, Savannah is literally
block to block to block.

00:52:12.310 --> 00:52:13.419
Yep. Yep.

00:52:13.425 --> 00:52:15.778
-And then it's all of a sudden
a different world.

00:52:15.778 --> 00:52:16.778
-Mm-hmm.

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:18.400
-What's this neighborhood?

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:22.497
-This is cool. This is Carver Village,
but this is West Savannah, Augusta Avenue.

00:52:22.497 --> 00:52:23.970
This is a old jail.

00:52:24.470 --> 00:52:26.525
It's actually probably still in play where

00:52:26.968 --> 00:52:28.298
halfway house is what it is.

00:52:28.298 --> 00:52:31.075
When you're about to get out of prison,
they bring you here.

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:33.604
-I don't know what we crossed,
the highway or something.

00:52:33.604 --> 00:52:35.818
-Totally changed.
-We came across the ViDoc.

00:52:36.302 --> 00:52:37.648
Okay, the ViDoc. Mm-hmm.

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:41.493
And so this is West Savannah.
And we're going towards the ports.

00:52:41.493 --> 00:52:45.309
-Now, you're not gonna see,
with the houses, any refurbishing in it,

00:52:45.309 --> 00:52:47.610
unless it's Black people refurbishing it.

00:52:47.610 --> 00:52:49.430
-Okay, why is that? Too far away?

00:52:49.430 --> 00:52:51.102
Yeah, they don't have any interest in it.

00:52:51.102 --> 00:52:53.500
-So the gentrification
hasn't come out here yet.

00:52:53.500 --> 00:52:56.490
-Right. And a lot of it is,
you can't change any of this stuff.

00:52:56.490 --> 00:52:58.129
There's a lot of violence out here.

00:52:58.613 --> 00:53:00.399
A lot of poverty out here.

00:53:00.399 --> 00:53:01.802
And that's the biggest thing, man.

00:53:01.802 --> 00:53:04.877
We've never,
not only have been taught to get out,

00:53:04.877 --> 00:53:08.219
we've never
given an opportunity to get out.

00:53:08.780 --> 00:53:09.670
-Okay, but…

00:53:09.670 --> 00:53:14.933
And we can't turn around and say,
we'll look at you, because I'm one person.

00:53:15.430 --> 00:53:19.227
I'm just saying, it comes from the parents,
and if the parents say, hey, let's get out

00:53:19.227 --> 00:53:20.877
and go to the ocean this weekend,

00:53:21.507 --> 00:53:24.570
then the kids will go with the parents
to the ocean that weekend.

00:53:24.570 --> 00:53:25.794
It doesn't take much.

00:53:26.220 --> 00:53:28.720
Some people are so poor
they can't do it. I get it.

00:53:29.150 --> 00:53:31.610
But who's supposed to do it for them?

00:53:31.610 --> 00:53:35.045
That's so funny you say that.
My priest used to take me to the beach.

00:53:35.390 --> 00:53:39.342
-There you go. 
-My priest used to take me to restaurants.

00:53:39.730 --> 00:53:44.326
My priest used to buy me gifts
and tell me I was worth something.

00:53:44.580 --> 00:53:46.923
My mother was there,
but my mother was working.

00:53:46.923 --> 00:53:48.090
My mother was cleaning.

00:53:48.090 --> 00:53:51.422
My mother was being
mom and dad at the same time.

00:53:52.555 --> 00:53:55.476
-So it was these role models in your life

00:53:56.068 --> 00:53:58.177
that exposed you to these things

00:53:58.178 --> 00:54:00.268
that made you turn out
the way you turned out.

00:54:00.268 --> 00:54:01.718
-Exactly.
-So I'm just saying…

00:54:02.903 --> 00:54:06.300
If you bring kids into the world,
that's your responsibility.

00:54:06.300 --> 00:54:07.513
Like, that's how I look at it.

00:54:07.513 --> 00:54:11.330
If I bring kids into the world,
I'm not gonna rely on anyone else for that.

00:54:11.330 --> 00:54:14.680
Hopefully there will be more people
that come into those kid's lives

00:54:15.125 --> 00:54:16.375
that can be part of that.

00:54:17.650 --> 00:54:21.100
But nobody owes anyone anything,
in my opinion.

00:54:21.430 --> 00:54:24.420
I don't agree with that because

00:54:24.760 --> 00:54:27.540
there's just been
so many people taken advantage of

00:54:27.541 --> 00:54:29.686
and had things taken from them.

00:54:30.110 --> 00:54:31.878
And again, we're talking about real estate.

00:54:31.878 --> 00:54:33.160
We're talking about land.

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:36.610
And you'll be able to tell,
even the houses that have been fixed on,

00:54:36.610 --> 00:54:40.410
you can tell they don't have
the best quality of work either.

00:54:40.410 --> 00:54:42.780
You know, I'm doing what I can afford.

00:54:42.780 --> 00:54:44.856
Or I'm doing it piece by piece.

00:54:44.856 --> 00:54:45.910
Or look at that.

00:54:45.910 --> 00:54:49.770
A lot of people are just like, man,
I can't afford to clean my yard every week.

00:54:50.286 --> 00:54:51.286
Well,

00:54:52.670 --> 00:54:55.410
you can clean your yard.
You don't have to pay anyone for that.

00:54:55.410 --> 00:54:56.410
Yeah. Yeah.

00:54:57.345 --> 00:55:01.770
So it's crazy to think
a lot of high-paying jobs right near this.

00:55:01.770 --> 00:55:03.470
-The ports are very close.
-Mm-hmm.

00:55:03.898 --> 00:55:06.648
We're rolling up on
the International Longshoremen Hall.

00:55:07.260 --> 00:55:10.970
This is one of the few places where you can
have a record or even a federal record

00:55:10.971 --> 00:55:14.314
and you can still find a job
if you know someone

00:55:14.314 --> 00:55:18.598
and someone brings you in and make
a couple of hundred thousand dollars a year

00:55:19.084 --> 00:55:20.708
by being a longshoreman.

00:55:20.708 --> 00:55:22.834
-So you don't need
a college education for that?

00:55:22.834 --> 00:55:25.233
You don't even need
a high school diploma to do this.

00:55:25.233 --> 00:55:27.457
-And you can have a record.

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:28.730
Correct. Correct.

00:55:29.220 --> 00:55:31.710
I think it's very dangerous work,
but it's worth it to…

00:55:32.160 --> 00:55:34.290
-And you can make a couple hundred a year?
-Yeah.

00:55:34.290 --> 00:55:36.099
Do you know how many guys
that have done that?

00:55:36.099 --> 00:55:38.237
Yeah. I know that guy that
drives this Van right here.

00:55:38.237 --> 00:55:39.072
-This one?
-Yeah.

00:55:39.700 --> 00:55:42.039
You can see the money going into some of
these trucks, huh?

00:55:42.039 --> 00:55:44.251
-Yeah, of course. 
-The Harley Davidson Ford.

00:55:44.251 --> 00:55:46.101
They all try to out-money each other.

00:55:46.540 --> 00:55:49.508
My Uncle George,
he said he was coming out to meet me here.

00:55:54.606 --> 00:55:55.606
[JoJo] What's up?

00:55:56.232 --> 00:55:58.279
-[George] How are you?
-I had surgery.

00:55:58.820 --> 00:56:01.372
-Can I hang this from your…
-Yeah, yeah, yeah. Okay.

00:56:02.210 --> 00:56:04.686
So we're just doing a…
I'm with JoJo all day.

00:56:05.220 --> 00:56:07.388
He's showing me the city,
showing me his story.

00:56:07.388 --> 00:56:08.047
Yeah.

00:56:08.047 --> 00:56:11.755
And then a big part of Savannah
right now is the ports, right?

00:56:11.755 --> 00:56:13.940
-Yeah. Mm-hmm.
-Super active? What's going on here?

00:56:13.940 --> 00:56:15.566
Oh, yeah, yeah. We…

00:56:16.066 --> 00:56:19.480
I think we've got about
3,300 employees here, probably.

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:22.139
Are you operating one of those cranes,
or what do you do out there?

00:56:22.139 --> 00:56:24.397
Oh, no, no. My job…
That's Georgia Ports over there.

00:56:24.397 --> 00:56:25.256
-Okay.

00:56:25.256 --> 00:56:27.658
But we just work under the crane
and beside the crane.

00:56:27.658 --> 00:56:30.779
But we've got some new development
coming up where we're going…

00:56:30.779 --> 00:56:34.020
ILA is going to be actually
operating the crane.

00:56:34.020 --> 00:56:36.029
Container ships come in.
You're unloading.

00:56:36.029 --> 00:56:38.330
-Yeah. Unloading. Right.
-It's hitting trucks.

00:56:38.330 --> 00:56:41.118
Putting in trucks, flatbeds, or whatever.

00:56:41.580 --> 00:56:44.225
It's a union job.
So you gotta to wait till…

00:56:44.225 --> 00:56:45.815
-You get full bennies.
-Yeah.

00:56:45.815 --> 00:56:46.815
-Retirement.
-Yeah.

00:56:47.600 --> 00:56:49.520
-Everything.
-How long you been here?

00:56:49.520 --> 00:56:50.758
About 36 years.

00:56:50.758 --> 00:56:51.758
Wow.

00:56:52.190 --> 00:56:55.240
-So it's been good to you?
-Oh, yeah. I'm a supervisor. I'm a header.

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:58.812
So I don't have to, you know, 
do all the hard, hard work.

00:56:59.403 --> 00:57:03.264
I just pick up the men, go in,
placing them on ships, on jobs,

00:57:03.870 --> 00:57:05.364
and bringing some up from the hall.

00:57:05.364 --> 00:57:06.863
So we're hiring every day.

00:57:07.360 --> 00:57:10.299
But, you know,
it just means that already in place,

00:57:10.299 --> 00:57:12.517
already we have seniority.

00:57:13.030 --> 00:57:14.270
We have seniority.

00:57:14.270 --> 00:57:18.076
-JoJo was saying some guys
make upwards of $200,000 in here.

00:57:18.863 --> 00:57:19.957
Yeah. Easy.

00:57:19.957 --> 00:57:21.313
-Easy?
-Yeah.

00:57:21.740 --> 00:57:23.973
Okay.
So you're saying you take your money here.

00:57:23.973 --> 00:57:26.326
-You put enough time in. It's good money.
-Yeah.

00:57:26.326 --> 00:57:28.110
-You're saying flipping real estate.
-Yeah.

00:57:28.110 --> 00:57:30.340
I buy it. Fix them up. Flip them.

00:57:30.750 --> 00:57:32.937
You can to do real estate,
whatever you want to do.

00:57:32.937 --> 00:57:35.060
Go and get you a dealership if you want.

00:57:35.060 --> 00:57:36.878
A little small, mini dealership.

00:57:37.215 --> 00:57:39.362
-Like car dealership?
-Yeah. Used cars.

00:57:39.362 --> 00:57:42.940
Especially this time of year would be good
to go and do it now because income tax.

00:57:43.260 --> 00:57:46.125
Okay. What about the young guys?
Are they getting into this?

00:57:46.125 --> 00:57:47.601
Oh, yeah. Oh, yeah.

00:57:47.601 --> 00:57:50.131
We got a whole lot of guys.
I'm picking up young guys now.

00:57:50.131 --> 00:57:52.040
-Cool.
-I'm picking them to come and go to work.

00:57:52.040 --> 00:57:54.299
I see a lot of women
like I've never seen before.

00:57:54.299 --> 00:57:56.325
I haven't come down here in a long time.

00:57:56.325 --> 00:57:59.988
Yeah. Women are getting into it
because  they can drive trucks.

00:58:00.488 --> 00:58:02.550
They might not be able
to do like the lashing stuff

00:58:02.550 --> 00:58:05.050
like on the ship
with the containers and stuff like that.

00:58:05.050 --> 00:58:06.990
You know, all the manly stuff.

00:58:06.990 --> 00:58:07.735
-Right.

00:58:07.735 --> 00:58:12.815
But they can stand by the ship
and do ship side and get in trucks.

00:58:12.815 --> 00:58:14.355
And they can also head too.

00:58:14.935 --> 00:58:16.790
We got women that are supervisors.

00:58:16.790 --> 00:58:20.459
They've been here a long time
and they come up through the rank

00:58:20.983 --> 00:58:22.706
and say,
"Hey, you want to be a supervisor?"

00:58:22.706 --> 00:58:24.683
Yeah. I wouldn't turn it down.

00:58:25.052 --> 00:58:26.990
You're getting more money. [chuckles]

00:58:26.990 --> 00:58:29.448
But the guys just hang out right here.

00:58:29.448 --> 00:58:31.416
You know, they call.

00:58:31.416 --> 00:58:32.778
-Yeah. What are they doing?

00:58:32.779 --> 00:58:35.020
-Hanging out.
-For what? They're waiting for the ship?

00:58:35.020 --> 00:58:37.541
Waiting on a job.
Waiting for the ship to come.

00:58:37.541 --> 00:58:39.918
We have about four or five
checkouts during the day.

00:58:39.918 --> 00:58:41.145
-Four or five.
-Okay.

00:58:41.145 --> 00:58:45.119
5:00 in the morning,
6:00 in the morning, 8:00, 12:00.

00:58:45.119 --> 00:58:47.719
-[JoJo] But you have to be here.
-You got to be here.

00:58:48.330 --> 00:58:49.722
[Peter] This is your buddy, right?

00:58:49.722 --> 00:58:52.130
-See, we wear the same shoes.
Of course it is.

00:58:52.130 --> 00:58:53.966
-You work out here.
-I do.

00:58:53.966 --> 00:58:55.379
Okay. What's going on with this?

00:58:55.379 --> 00:58:58.252
-All right. So this is
the work order board for tonight.

00:58:58.673 --> 00:59:01.300
These are the ships that are
gonna start working tonight.

00:59:01.300 --> 00:59:02.662
And the way to read it is

00:59:03.227 --> 00:59:05.883
CBO6 is container berth six.

00:59:05.883 --> 00:59:06.940
-Okay.
-Right.

00:59:06.940 --> 00:59:09.152
And the name of the ship is the Cisnes.

00:59:09.673 --> 00:59:13.806
And these are the actual
supervisors or what we call headers.

00:59:14.320 --> 00:59:15.320
That'll be

00:59:15.894 --> 00:59:18.594
hiring the men to come work
in these particular crafts.

00:59:19.415 --> 00:59:22.210
These four will be picking up two men,

00:59:22.643 --> 00:59:24.693
which are the guys who go up on the ship

00:59:25.130 --> 00:59:27.222
to handle anything dealing with the shoes.

00:59:27.223 --> 00:59:30.872
The metal shoes, the locking devices
that goes in the bottom of the containers.

00:59:30.872 --> 00:59:31.563
-Okay.

00:59:31.563 --> 00:59:35.008
To keep the container secure
when they're on the top of the ship.

00:59:35.008 --> 00:59:38.505
These next four
will be hiring six men each,

00:59:39.112 --> 00:59:40.112
which are lashers.

00:59:41.358 --> 00:59:42.890
That's primarily what I do.

00:59:42.890 --> 00:59:46.772
We're the guys that go up on the ship
to disconnect the containers.

00:59:47.119 --> 00:59:50.988
These four here are hiring
seven truck drivers.

00:59:50.988 --> 00:59:53.566
So these seven men or women

00:59:53.566 --> 00:59:57.360
will all be driving jockey trucks
that take the containers

00:59:57.361 --> 00:59:59.760
from the ship out to the stacks.

00:59:59.760 --> 01:00:03.680
So the basic mechanics, this is one of
the biggest ports in the country, right?

01:00:03.680 --> 01:00:04.680
That's right.

01:00:04.680 --> 01:00:06.433
How many ships come in in a day, roughly?

01:00:06.690 --> 01:00:10.000
Anywhere from nine on up on an average day.

01:00:10.310 --> 01:00:12.800
-Without you guys,
everything stops in this country.

01:00:12.800 --> 01:00:14.450
-Everything we use.
-That's right.

01:00:14.843 --> 01:00:16.810
We're the first to touch the cargo.
Absolutely.

01:00:16.810 --> 01:00:18.395
So it's a very important thing.

01:00:18.395 --> 01:00:20.010
It's extremely important.

01:00:20.010 --> 01:00:22.250
-Do you guys feel pride in your job?
-Absolutely.

01:00:22.250 --> 01:00:25.301
We're the second largest
revenue generator in the state

01:00:25.301 --> 01:00:27.904
behind the Atlanta-Hartsfield Airport.

01:00:27.904 --> 01:00:29.663
-No way. Wow.
-Absolutely.

01:00:29.963 --> 01:00:31.616
So it's a brotherhood.
You know everyone?

01:00:31.616 --> 01:00:33.701
Yeah, pretty much. Family.

01:00:33.701 --> 01:00:35.602
Thanks for your time. Anytime, man.

01:00:35.602 --> 01:00:39.046
Catch me a little early next time and
I'll make it happen. We'll get you inside.

01:00:39.046 --> 01:00:40.046
-Thank you.

01:00:43.280 --> 01:00:47.208
Okay, what I asked you before
off camera was no Hispanics here,

01:00:47.208 --> 01:00:49.527
no Whites here, only Black working, right?

01:00:49.527 --> 01:00:51.188
I haven't seen one pass through yet.

01:00:51.188 --> 01:00:52.860
Right. Okay, so what's that?

01:00:52.860 --> 01:00:56.056
You can see what's funny.
Like these guys, he's going to work.

01:00:56.056 --> 01:00:59.180
You know, but he's got a leather,
clean white leather jacket on.

01:00:59.180 --> 01:01:00.225
-Yeah, he looks spiffy.

01:01:00.225 --> 01:01:02.711
But see, those are the guys
that he's talking about the headers

01:01:02.711 --> 01:01:06.080
and you can tell they're not doing
any work, just pointing fingers.

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:08.120
And then when it's all
said and done, they'll go out

01:01:08.120 --> 01:01:11.355
and either go home and go to bed
or come out here and goof off.

01:01:11.355 --> 01:01:15.800
But the guys that are really doing the work
are the guys that you see dressed to work.

01:01:16.130 --> 01:01:19.880
Okay, so why are there
no White dudes here or no Hispanics?

01:01:19.880 --> 01:01:22.792
Because they decide who works there or not.

01:01:23.137 --> 01:01:24.356
-You know what I mean?
-Okay.

01:01:24.356 --> 01:01:27.067
If I wanted to work, I would strictly
have to go through my uncle

01:01:27.067 --> 01:01:28.385
or go through James.

01:01:28.385 --> 01:01:30.741
-Okay, so there's
some nepotism going on here.

01:01:30.741 --> 01:01:32.260
-Right, absolutely.
-Okay.

01:01:32.635 --> 01:01:35.044
And it's one of
the best gigs in town, right?

01:01:35.044 --> 01:01:37.624
Yeah. Again, especially if
you've got a criminal record

01:01:37.624 --> 01:01:40.187
or if you, you know,
don't have an education.

01:01:40.540 --> 01:01:44.125
But James is the cream of the crop here
because he has both.

01:01:44.125 --> 01:01:46.979
You know, he's very well spoken,
has education, you know.

01:01:46.979 --> 01:01:47.979
Yeah.

01:01:48.390 --> 01:01:50.032
And then you get all these food tents.

01:01:50.032 --> 01:01:52.780
So people are just spending
a lot of time out here.

01:01:52.780 --> 01:01:53.780
Yeah.

01:01:57.746 --> 01:02:00.419
JoJo, this is just
right out of the city basically.

01:02:00.419 --> 01:02:01.220
-Right.

01:02:01.220 --> 01:02:03.722
Some of the big money
will have their homes out here, right?

01:02:03.722 --> 01:02:05.196
15 minutes outside of the city.

01:02:05.196 --> 01:02:06.746
-15 minutes.
-This is old money.

01:02:07.280 --> 01:02:08.879
[Peter] Guys,
we're doing our best here.

01:02:08.879 --> 01:02:12.734
The sun is going down, but we'll be able
to show a little bit at least.

01:02:13.690 --> 01:02:17.910
[JoJo] The people that are living here now
have gotten these homes from their parents.

01:02:18.741 --> 01:02:20.324
-Some cool places out here.

01:02:20.324 --> 01:02:23.028
-Yeah, we're going to come up
to a gate pretty soon.

01:02:23.028 --> 01:02:26.112
-You have all these swamps
and that limits development.

01:02:26.763 --> 01:02:28.600
[JoJo] They don't want development here.

01:02:28.600 --> 01:02:30.950
They want to be alone,
they want to be by themselves.

01:02:30.950 --> 01:02:32.049
-Right.

01:02:32.049 --> 01:02:35.299
-They want you to have to be able
to call before you just show up.

01:02:39.380 --> 01:02:41.857
-Check it out, JoJo.
-They don't seem that afraid of people.

01:02:41.857 --> 01:02:44.620
Yeah, they're really,
they're people deer, that's for sure.

01:02:44.620 --> 01:02:45.620
Look at these guys.

01:02:46.486 --> 01:02:48.430
[JoJo] Like you got some food, buddy,
or what?

01:02:48.430 --> 01:02:50.787
-All right, JoJo,
we ran out of light, but thank you.

01:02:50.787 --> 01:02:52.119
Appreciate it.

01:02:52.126 --> 01:02:54.564
-Good tour today.
-Absolutely.

01:02:54.564 --> 01:02:58.294
And off camera you were saying,
you were talking about your foundation.

01:02:58.294 --> 01:02:59.175
There you go.

01:02:59.175 --> 01:03:01.161
I want the audience to know
what you're doing.

01:03:01.161 --> 01:03:03.720
Well, we've got the JoJo Jones Foundation.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:09.216
If you want to check us out,
it's www.jojojonesfoundation.com.

01:03:09.880 --> 01:03:12.781
Definitely check us out.
See what we have for young people.

01:03:12.781 --> 01:03:15.024
What comes with young people
comes parenting,

01:03:15.024 --> 01:03:16.940
and family, and so on, and so forth.

01:03:16.940 --> 01:03:19.955
So our main goal is learning
to talk to each other.

01:03:19.955 --> 01:03:22.893
The scripture talks about
words being a double-edged sword.

01:03:22.893 --> 01:03:24.887
And it's all about
how we connect with each other.

01:03:24.887 --> 01:03:28.230
It's all about how we talk to each other.
It's even about how we sing to each other.

01:03:28.230 --> 01:03:30.774
And that even comes back to our music

01:03:30.774 --> 01:03:33.396
and the way we take care of people
through rhythm and rhyme.

01:03:33.396 --> 01:03:37.215
So check us out
and you'll see exactly what we mean

01:03:37.216 --> 01:03:38.681
when it comes to communication,

01:03:38.681 --> 01:03:41.070
verbal communication
and non-verbal communication.

01:03:41.070 --> 01:03:42.286
Awesome, JoJo.

01:03:42.286 --> 01:03:45.351
And that was not your normal Savannah tour.

01:03:45.658 --> 01:03:48.842
So thank you for that.
I think we saw a lot of different slices.

01:03:48.842 --> 01:03:52.129
Unfortunately, we can't get into
the hamstring pulling

01:03:52.129 --> 01:03:56.192
and the cigarette smoking
and the lack of understanding.

01:03:56.192 --> 01:03:59.212
My hamstrings
definitely feel pulled right now.

01:03:59.212 --> 01:04:01.748
-But it was worth it.
-I'll be laughing in my sleep about that.

01:04:01.748 --> 01:04:02.736
Absolutely.

01:04:02.736 --> 01:04:04.820
Guys, thanks for coming on that journey.

01:04:04.820 --> 01:04:06.315
Until the next one.

01:04:06.315 --> 01:04:07.315
Thank you, guys.

01:04:07.735 --> 01:04:08.735
[country music]

